VERDICT: confirmed-but-no-uca
REASON: Both defects reproduce on HEAD. D1: src/spinlock_validate.rs:109-129, 154-172, 188-203 list requires cpu_id_valid(current_cpu_id) (cpu < MAX_CPUS=4) as a Verus precondition, but the three extern "C" wrappers at ffi/src/lib.rs:8904-8945 forward thread_cpu and current_cpu_id to the verified Rust functions with no runtime guard, and the Zephyr shim at zephyr/gale_spinlock_validate.c:33-34,60-61,66-67 passes _current_cpu->id through unfiltered. The upstream BUILD_ASSERT at /Users/r/git/pulseengine/z/zephyr/include/zephyr/spinlock.h:107 is gated by #ifdef CONFIG_SPIN_VALIDATE (lines 103, 113), so it is absent for direct FFI consumers and any CONFIG_SPIN_VALIDATE=n build that still routes through gale_spin_lock_compute_owner. D2: CPU_MASK is hard-coded to 3 at src/spinlock_validate.rs:47 with the docstring at lines 8-10,27,41 inviting widening of MAX_CPUS; for current_cpu_id>=4 the expression (thread_cpu & CPU_MASK) ∈ {0..3} cannot equal current_cpu_id, so spin_lock_valid always returns true on same-CPU reacquire — SV2 violated. The existing Kani harnesses at ffi/src/lib.rs:9117-9219 all begin with kani::assume(cpu_id < 4), so they reinforce the same blind spot rather than exposing it. The finding is interesting: it is not a documented caller-responsibility contract (the FFI docstring at 8896-8901 and gale_spinlock_validate.c:11-14 advertise validation, not a cpu<4 prerequisite); ARM Cortex-M SMP parts with >4 cores exist within the declared target family (safety_case.yaml:C-1); no artifacts/ entry documents it as a known limitation. Cannot map to an existing UCA: safety/stpa/ucas.yaml does not exist, and artifacts/stpa.yaml explicitly scopes UCAs out ("Control structure, UCAs, and loss scenarios are out of scope for this initial artifact"). Recommend filing SVAL-UCA-1 ("spinlock validator returns valid=true while the lock is held by the current CPU", STPA UCA-type 2, feeding H-4 / L-3) together with the SMP-UCA-3/4 suggested by the smp_state verdict, forming the initial UCA block.
